<p></p>.<p>Symptoms of hyperthermia, or <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/hyperthermia/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">heat-related illness</a>, vary according to the specific type of illness. The most severe form of hyperthermia is <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/heat_stroke/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">heat stroke</a>. This happens when the body is no longer able to regulate its internal temperature; 
this is a medical emergency. The body temperature may be over 105 F, a level that damages the brain and other organs. Other symptoms include <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/muscle_cramps/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">muscle cramps</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/fatigue/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">fatigue</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/dizziness_dizzy/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">dizziness</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/headache/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">headache</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/nausea_and_vomiting/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">nausea</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/nausea_and_vomiting/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">vomiting</a>, and <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/weakness/symptoms.htm" rel="sym" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">weakness</a>. The heart rate may be elevated, and the skin is reddened. The skin may be moist if <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/hyperhidrosis_sweating_pictures_slideshow/article.htm" rel="slide" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">sweating</a> is still occurring, or it may be dry if <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/sweating_perspiration_quiz/quiz.htm" rel="quiz" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">sweating</a> has stopped. <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/confusion/symptoms.htm" rel="sym" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Confusion</a> and mental changes may develop, and 
<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/seizures_symptoms_and_types/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">seizures</a> can occur with <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/brain_damage_symptoms_causes_treatment/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">brain damage</a>. Ultimately, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/coma/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">coma</a> and death may ensue.</p>.<p>
<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/heat_exhaustion/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Heat exhaustion</a> is a less severe form of hyperthermia. People with heat exhaustion typically experience weakness, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/nausea/symptoms.htm" rel="sym" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">nausea</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/vomiting/symptoms.htm" rel="sym" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">vomiting</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/migraine_headaches_pictures_slideshow/article.htm" rel="slide" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">headache</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/muscle_cramps/symptoms.htm" rel="sym" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">muscle cramps</a>, and 
profuse sweating. Other forms of heat illness include <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/heat_cramps/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">heat cramps</a>, which are involuntary spasms of large muscle groups, and heat <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/fainting/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">syncope</a>, which is <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/fainting/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">fainting</a> or <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/dizziness_dizzy/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">lightheadedness</a>. <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/heat_rash/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Heat rash</a> is characterized by a prickly or 
<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/itch/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">itchy</a> feeling of the skin coupled with red 
<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/bumps_on_skin/symptoms.htm" rel="sym" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">bumps on the skin</a>.</p>.<p class="credits">REFERENCE:<br><br>
United States. National Institutes of Health. "Hyperthermia: Too Hot for Your Health." June 27, 2012. &lt;http://www.nih.gov/news/health/jun2012/nia-27.htm&gt;.</p>